A systematic meta-analysis of genetic, regional, and production determinants of global pork quality

Code and model outputs - Meat Redness (a* value)

1 Loading packages and data

## Load the packages
library(metafor)
library(orchaRd)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(kableExtra)
library(knitr)
library(openxlsx)
library(MuMIn)
library(glue)
library(rlang)
library(purrr)
library(tibble)
## Load the functions from the script file
source("functions.R")
## Load the data for meat redness (a*)
data_A <- read.csv("A.csv")

## Convert columns to appropriate numeric types
data_A$Mean <- as.numeric(data_A$Mean)
data_A$SD <- as.numeric(data_A$SD)
data_A$Sample <- as.numeric(data_A$Sample)
data_A$Age <- as.numeric(data_A$Age)
data_A$Weight <- as.numeric(data_A$Weight)
data_A$Digestible_energy <- as.numeric(data_A$Digestible_energy)
data_A$Crude_protein <- as.numeric(data_A$Crude_protein)
data_A$Crude_fat <- as.numeric(data_A$Crude_fat)
data_A$Crude_fiber <- as.numeric(data_A$Crude_fiber)
data_A$Ash <- as.numeric(data_A$Ash)
data_A$Lys <- as.numeric(data_A$Lys)
data_A$Met_and_Cys <- as.numeric(data_A$Met_and_Cys)
data_A$Thr <- as.numeric(data_A$Thr)
data_A$Try <- as.numeric(data_A$Try)
data_A$Val <- as.numeric(data_A$Val)
data_A$Dry_matter <- as.numeric(data_A$Dry_matter)
data_A$Ca <- as.numeric(data_A$Ca)
data_A$P <- as.numeric(data_A$P)
data_A$Na <- as.numeric(data_A$Na)

## Convert columns to factor types
data_A$Position <- factor(data_A$Position)
data_A$Breed <- factor(data_A$Breed)
data_A$Class <- factor(data_A$Class)
data_A$Sex <- factor(data_A$Sex)
data_A$Region <- factor(data_A$Region)
data_A$Aim <- factor(data_A$Aim)
data_A$Multiple_breeds <- factor(data_A$Multiple_breeds)

## Calculate variance (rVar)
# rVar is the square of the standard error (SD/sqrt(Sample))
data_A$rVar <- (data_A$SD / sqrt(data_A$Sample))^2

2 Testing random effects

## Run VCV matrix for all data
VCV_A_AllData <- make_VCV_matrix(data_A, 
                                 V = "rVar", 
                                 cluster = "StudyID", 
                                 obs = "RowID")

## Null model with VCV matrix:
# This model includes random effects for RowID (observation-level) and StudyID.
null_A_mod <- rma.mv(yi = Mean, 
                     V = VCV_A_AllData, 
                     random = list(~1 | RowID,
                                   ~1 | StudyID),
                     sparse = TRUE,
                     data = data_A, 
                     method = "ML")

R2_models_summary <- data.frame("Model" = c("Full",
                                     "Position",
                                     "Breed",
                                     "Area",
                                     "Class"),
                         "R2" = c(R2_Full[1],
                                  R2_Position[1],
                                  R2_Breed[1],
                                  R2_Region[1], 
                                  R2_Class[1]))
R2_models_summary <- R2_models_summary %>% 
  transmute(Model = Model
            ,R2= round(R2,2))

colnames(R2_models_summary)[2] <- "$R^2(\\%)$"

R2_models_summary %>% 
  kable(format="html", escape=F, caption="Heterogeneity explained in the models with moderators") %>% 
  collapse_rows(columns = 1, valign = "top") %>% 
  kable_styling(c("hover", "condensed"), full_width = F)

## Refit with REML for reporting in Manuscript
REML_A_mod <- rma.mv(yi = Mean, 
                     V = VCV_A_AllData, 
                     random = list(~1 | RowID,
                                   ~1 | StudyID,
                                   ~1 | Region,
                                   # ~1 | Breed, # Breed was not better than null in initial test
                                   ~1 | Position),
                     sparse = TRUE,
                     data = data_A, 
                     method = "REML")

3 Meta-regression

3.1 Breed

## Filter data for breeds with at least 3 distinct StudyIDs
data_A_B3 <- data_A %>%
  group_by(Breed) %>%
  filter(n_distinct(StudyID) >= 3) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  as.data.frame()

## Create VCV matrix for the filtered breed data
VCV_A_B3_Data <- make_VCV_matrix(data_A_B3, 
                                 V = "rVar", 
                                 cluster = "StudyID", 
                                 obs = "RowID")
## Define random structure
random_structure_breed <- list(~1 | RowID,
                               ~1 | StudyID,
                               ~1 | Region,
                               ~1 | Position)

# Model with intercept
Br_VCV_REML_A_mod_int <- rma.mv(
  yi = Mean,
  V = VCV_A_B3_Data,
  mods = ~ Breed,
  random = random_structure_breed,
  test = "t",
  method = "REML",
  data = data_A_B3)

summary(Br_VCV_REML_A_mod_int)

  mods      = mods_list_age, 
  aic_tab   = aic_tab_age,
  lin_coef  = "mod_c",              
  quad_coef = "mod_c2"
)

html_table_age <- tbl_A_Age %>%

4 Publication bias and sensitivty analyses

4.1 Decline effect (Publication Year)

## Define random structure
random_structure_Ye <- list(~1 | RowID,
                            ~1 | StudyID,
                            ~1 | Region,
                            ~1 | Position)

## Model with Publication Year (Years) as moderator
Ye_VCV_REML_A_mod_int <- rma.mv(
  yi = Mean,
  V = VCV_A_AllData,
  mods = ~ Years,
  random = random_structure_Ye,
  test = "t",
  method = "REML",
  data = data_A
)
summary(Ye_VCV_REML_A_mod_int)

##

## 
##              estim    sqrt  nlvls  fixed    factor

## sigma^2.2  14.9437  3.8657    259     no   StudyID 
## sigma^2.3   8.0786  2.8423     46     no    Region 
## sigma^2.4  11.0721  3.3275     15     no  Position 
## 
## Test for Residual Heterogeneity:
## QE(df = 487) = 298200.9901, p-val < .0001
##

## F(df1 = 1, df2 = 487) = 3.3400, p-val = 0.0682
## 
## Model Results:
## 
##           estimate        se     tval   df    pval      ci.lb    ci.ub
